<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMPUTER FILE: GEOWORKS GETS A LOT MORE FROM LESS POWER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LAWRENCE J. MAGID, LAWRENCE J. MAGID is a Silicon Valley-based computer 
analyst and writer. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GeoWorks, a 50-person software company based in Berkeley, is about to release 
GeoWorks Ensemble, a set of programs and an exciting new graphical user 
interface for IBM PCs and compatibles. The product, which will be unveiled this 
evening in Boston, should be available in November. 
</P>
<P>
Because of its modest hardware requirements, GeoWorks will be of particular 
interest to people with older machines as well as budget-minded computer 
shoppers who are looking for an easy-to-use environment that runs on low-cost 
equipment. The product is aimed at the home and small-business market. But even 
users of more powerful machines will appreciate GeoWorks' simplicity, speed and 
excellent graphics. 
</P>
<P>
In general, GeoWorks is similar to what is already available on the Apple 
Macintosh or on IBM compatibles running Microsoft Windows. You start programs 
by using a mouse to click on their icons, or pictures. Commands are issued via 
pull-down menus. You use the mouse to select text or graphics to be copied, 
deleted or moved. And data can be easily moved from one program to another. 
What's more, it's possible to run more than one program at a time, each in its 
own window and switch from program to program with a click of the mouse. 
GeoWorks will have a suggested retail price of $195. 
</P>
<P>
Unlike Windows, GeoWorks works on virtually any IBM PC as long as it has a hard 
disk, a graphic display and at least 512 kilobytes of memory. Windows requires 
a PC with at least 1 megabyte of memory and an Intel 286, 386 or 486 central 
processing unit. As a result, most machines in use today are not able to run 
Windows. 
</P>
<P>
My only complaint about GeoWorks is that it doesn't allow you to create macros, 
which allow you to assign your own series of keystrokes to commands. GeoWorks 
plans to add a macro feature to a future version. 
</P>
<P>
GeoWorks starts off with a "Welcome" screen with three icons. A click on the 
Appliances icon takes you to an area where you can use any of four basic and 
easy-to-use programs: a calculator, an address book, a personal 
calendar/planner and a note pad. The Professional icon takes you to the 
GeoManager, with icons for eight additional programs: word processing, 
computer-to-computer communications, drawing, personal calendar, address book, 
note pad, calculator and a program to connect with America Online, an 
easy-to-use on-line information service. It's also where you perform routine 
file maintenance such as copying, deleting and moving files or creating 
directories. 
</P>
<P>
The final icon on the Welcome screen takes you to an area where you can start 
regular MS-DOS programs that do not use the GeoWorks interface. 
</P>
<P>
GeoWorks' word processing program, called GeoWrite, is both easy to use and 
sophisticated. It compares favorably to stand-alone word-processing programs 
that sell for more than twice the cost of the entire GeoWorks package. As with 
all GeoWorks programs, its typefaces can be displayed or printed at any size. 
</P>
<P>
The "what you see is what you get" (WYSIWYG) environment displays your margins, 
headers, footers and page breaks. GeoWrite supports color and multiple columns 
on screen. You can create and store paragraph styles and ruler settings for use 
on subsequent documents. 
</P>
<P>
Text editing is similar to what you'll find on Macintosh and Windows 
word-processing programs. To modify text, you select it with the mouse and 
perform an operation such as copying it to the clipboard, deleting it or 
changing its appearance. 
</P>
<P>
The drawing program, called GeoDraw, is also reasonably sophisticated. You can 
use it to draw lines, circles, rectangles and other shapes in black and white 
or color. Any graphic created in GeoDraw can be pasted into GeoWrite or any 
other GeoWorks application. Drawing programs, unlike painting programs, allow 
you to create and manipulate objects so that any portion can be resized, 
deleted or moved without affecting other parts. 
</P>
<P>
The communications program, called GeoComm, is pretty basic but it's good 
enough for most users who want to sign on to an on-line service such as 
CompuServe, GEnie or MCI Mail. Another GeoWorks program is designed to sign on 
to America Online, which provides news, information, electronic mail and other 
services. America Online costs $5.95 a month plus a minimum of $5 per hour. 
</P>
<P>
GeoPlanner, the personal calendar program, and GeoDex, which stores phone 
numbers and addresses, are very basic and easy to use. The two programs can 
work together to both look up a person's number and dial the telephone if your 
PC is equipped with a modem. 
</P>
<P>
The company, according to its president, Brian Dougherty, is encouraging other 
software companies to develop additional GeoWorks programs, including a 
spreadsheet and database management system. 
</P>
<P>
GeoWorks is located at 2125 Shattuck Ave., Berkeley, Calif. 94704. Phone: (415) 
644-0883. 
</P>
<P>
Computer File welcomes readers' comments but regrets that the authors cannot 
respond individually to letters. Write to P.O. Box 620477, Woodside, Calif. 
94062, or contact the L. Magid account on the MCI electronic mail system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Portion of the GeoWorks programs 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
