<HEADLINE>
<P>
ERMA BOMBECK: EMPTY NEST GETS FAST REDECORATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERMA BOMBECK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For a long time sociologists had us believing that the "empty nest" was like 
some dreaded, uncontrollable disease, symptomatized by crying, long periods of 
depression and an inability to function. 
</P>
<P>
We'd hear stories about mothers who converted their grown children's rooms into 
shrines and fathers who called up their married sons and begged them to "come 
over and shoot a few baskets after dinner." 
</P>
<P>
Rumors circulated that mothers automatically set the table for three for the 
rest of their lives and dads gave up their bowling nights for fear they'd miss 
a call from the "kid." 
</P>
<P>
In my mind, I put the empty nest right up there with menopause and gingivitis. 
</P>
<P>
When our last child left home, a friend called and said, "You need company to 
get you through the first night alone?" 
</P>
<P>
"Actually," I said, "you caught us as we were leaving. We're going out to 
dinner." 
</P>
<P>
"You're going to have to face that empty house sometime," she warned. 
</P>
<P>
She was right. We filled in all the small holes left by darts and nails and had 
his room painted and made into a small TV room. We had the rugs cleaned and the 
oil spots removed from the driveway. After that, we went on our first vacation 
that wasn't planned around a paper route. 
</P>
<P>
I'm not saying there weren't adjustments. It was weeks before we stopped 
looking for the TV tuner in the bathroom, months before our hearing returned to 
normal, and I still haven't gotten over the shock of going into the garage and 
seeing my own car parked there. 
</P>
<P>
In retrospect, we have learned to live with phones that ring only when they're 
for us, two loads of laundry a week and popcorn for dinner. Our friends marvel 
at how well we are able to deal with the trauma of just the two of us entering 
the twilight years alone. They say we are very brave. We smile and say, "Thank 
you." 
</P>
<P>
Recently the University of Nebraska researched the empty-nest syndrome and 
discovered that when children leave home, the marriage of the parents not only 
improves, but that they may even experience a mini-honeymoon. 
</P>
<P>
Some say this change of attitude is due to the independence of women who go 
from child raising to a second career that is just as fulfilling. I say there 
was a whole generation of parents who were lying to us through their teeth just 
to keep the prophecy alive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA100490-0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 286963 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 4, 1990, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 2; Column 1; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
254 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: 'MISS DAISY' STILL BARRELING ALONG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DENNIS HUNT , Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When is "Driving Miss Daisy" going to run out of gas? The makers of the movies 
that have been vainly chasing "Miss Daisy" on the Billboard magazine rental 
chart since August would love to know. They'd like a chance to rule the rental 
chart, but none have had enough drawing power to unseat the queen -- "Miss 
Daisy." 
</P>
<P>
"Born on the Fourth of July," which has No. 1 potential, is still trailing in 
the No. 2 spot. The question is, will "Born" run out of steam before "Miss 
Daisy" runs out of gas? Tune in next week. Disney's "Peter Pan" flitted onto 
the rental chart at No. 17. But, retailing for $24.99 and often discounted down 
around $15, "Peter Pan" will do much better in the sales market. 
</P>
<P>
* "Born on the Fourth of July" hasn't had any luck driving "Miss Daisy" out of 
the top spot, but another kind of war movie might just do it. "Glory," which is 
about a black regiment in the Civil War, entered the chart at No. 6. Because 
the PBS "Civil War" TV series did so well last week, there's probably 
heightened interest among many renters in an acclaimed movie dealing with that 
war. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
VIDEO RENTALS 
</P>
