<HEADLINE>
<P>
'DIATRIBE' ON GRAND JURY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The scurrilous outburst in a letter of Aug. 5 aimed at the 1989-90 Ventura 
County Grand Jury, apparently written by labor organizer Barry Hammitt, can 
actually have one beneficial result. 
</P>
<P>
People may be stimulated to read the 1989-90 grand jury reports, especially the 
report on substance abuse, which seemed to be the major cause of this peculiar 
outburst. 
</P>
<P>
Readers should be making their own judgments about significant matters 
discussed in the reports in order to form their own opinions. 
</P>
<P>
As with any institution, even the 1,000-year-old grand jury system, review and 
reanalysis are always essential and vital to a democracy. I may, with 
apologies, refer to my own analysis, which was published in the July 11 issue 
of the News Chronicle of Thousand Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
Constructive change, however, is always the result of quiet reflection and 
civilized exchanges of views, not of explosive diatribes. 
</P>
<P>
L. EDWARD SHUCK 
</P>
<P>
Thousand Oaks 
</P>
<P>
Shuck was foreman pro tem of the 1989-90 Ventura County Grand Jury and chairman 
of its Health, Education and Welfare Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
