<HEADLINE>
<P>
MEMORIAL RITES FOR COMPTON MAYOR PLANNED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
COMPTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The body of Mayor Walter R. Tucker will lie in state today and Friday in the 
room where he spent so much time in the last nine years: the City Council 
chambers. 
</P>
<P>
Tucker was serving his third mayoral term when he died of cancer Monday at 66. 
</P>
<P>
A memorial service will be held Friday from noon to 2 p.m. in Civic Center 
Plaza outside the chambers. The body will lie in state today from 3 to 8 p.m. 
and on Friday from 10 a.m. to 8 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
Flags across the city will remain at half-staff all week until after the 11 
a.m. funeral Saturday at Eagle Rock Missionary Baptist Church in Compton. 
Burial will be at Angeles Abbey in Compton. 
</P>
<P>
In lieu of flowers, donations may be made in the mayor's memory to a 
scholarship fund created by his family. Those who wish to donate to the fund 
may call 285-3770. The mayor is survived by his wife, Martha; two daughters, 
Keta and Camille, and two sons, Walter and Kenneth. 
</P>
<P>
Tucker came to the city in 1957 and set up a dental practice, which he 
maintained until he became ill this year. 
</P>
<P>
He entered politics in 1967, winning election as a school trustee that year. In 
1973 he won a council seat but was later defeated in his first mayoral bid. 
When he ran again in 1981, he was elected mayor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Walter R. Tucker SARAH M. BROWN / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
