<SUBJECT>
<P>
CHICAGO -- DEVELOPMENT AND REDEVELOPMENT; HOUSING -- FEDERAL AID; FEDERAL 
HOUSING ADMINISTRATION; LOAN DEFAULTS; MORTGAGE INSURANCE 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA100490-0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 287291 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 4, 1990, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
100 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Federated, Allied Unveil Business Plan: Federated Department Stores Inc. and 
Allied Stores Corp. announced a plan to improve profitability that assumes 
Campeau Corp.'s U.S. retailers will emerge from bankruptcy next year. 
</P>
<P>
The plan, which covers the period through 1996, includes selected store 
closings but not the outright sale of any of its department store chains. These 
include such retailers as Bloomingdale's, Bon Marche, Burdines, Jordan Marsh, 
Lazurus and Rich's. Company spokesmen refused to say how much would be offered 
to creditors, who collectively are owed about $7.7 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
