<P>
SAN GABRIEL VALLEY DIGEST: MONROVIA; 
</P>
<P>
TRAFFIC VIOLATIONS TARGETED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Neighborhoods that draw complaints about repeated traffic violations will be 
targeted with signs and special police enforcement under a new program approved 
Tuesday by the City Council. The blue signs, which feature a silhouette of a 
police motorcycle, say "Special Traffic Enforcement Area" and ask motorists to 
"Please Obey All Laws." 
</P>
<P>
They will be posted in areas with traffic problems such as speeding or failure 
to stop for stop signs, Police Capt. Robert Page said. 
</P>
<P>
Along with the signs, there will be a heavy police presence in those areas for 
30 days, Page said. If the traffic problems do not diminish, the program can be 
extended. Up to 10 special enforcement areas can be established in the city at 
one time, Page said. 
</P>
