<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
MONACO REMAINS IN MOURNING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MONTE CARLO, Monaco 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The flag atop the royal palace flew at half-staff today as Monaco mourned the 
death of Princess Caroline's husband, Stefano Casiraghi, 30, in a speedboat 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
Several of the racers competing against Casiraghi in the World Offshore 
Championships said he was driving too fast Wednesday to handle the choppy water 
on the course. His boat somersaulted backward, and he was killed instantly. 
</P>
<P>
Residents of the principality, but not tourists, were allowed to file past 
Casiraghi's body in a mortuary near the Princess Grace hospital. He lay in a 
simple, brass-handled mahogany coffin, still wearing the red-and-white racing 
suit in which he died while defending his world title. There was a slight cut 
under one eye. 
</P>
</TEXT>
