<P>
CHINA BANS WEST BOOKS, TAPES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BEIJING 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Millions of books, tapes and videos have been banned in China's current 
campaign against Western and anti-Communist influences, according to a trade 
publication. 
</P>
<P>
The Oct. 3 edition of the biweekly Press and Publishing Journal, seen in 
Beijing today, said: "Good results have been achieved so far." 
</P>
<P>
Since the campaign began in August last year, more than 39 million books and 
magazines and 1.6 million music and video tapes have been banned, it said. 
</P>
<P>
"Some 2,500 outlets (producing banned material) have been smashed," it said. 
"This has played a vital role against bourgeois liberalism and peaceful 
evolution." 
</P>
<P>
Publishing houses have increased their output of Marxist works. "All these 
books are beneficial in cleaning people's minds as to who is right and who is 
wrong and maintaining stability," the journal said. 
</P>
